Lost in the Hollow Karst
[trigger none]

The karst doesn't have trails. It has routes, paths worn by herder clans who know this place well enough to name it in ways they won't say aloud to outsiders. What you have are tracks in old mud, cairns that may mark something or may mark nothing, and the creeping suspicion that the ground is not as solid as it presents itself. The limestone beneath your feet is honeycombed. Twice today you've stepped on what looked like solid ground and felt it shift, felt the hollow resonance of empty space below.

You have no idea how far you've come from the last settlement, or in what direction. The sky is overcast, flat and directionless, offering no shadows to read. You have studied the terrain around you for half an hour and cannot make it cohere into a map. The herder clans say that the Hollow Karst knows where you are even when you don't. You don't know what to make of that.

A fissure in the limestone offers shelter from the wind and is deep enough to see a cave mouth beyond: dry ground, out of the weather, but underground. To the east, a line of old clan markers, stacked stones in a specific arrangement, runs toward the ridge. Above, the cloud breaks briefly and you can see stars beginning against a pale twilight sky.

choices:

* Navigate by the stars = Wait for dark, read the sky, move when you know your direction
  You wedge yourself into the fissure out of the wind, pull your coat tight, and wait. The cloud thins and thickens by turns. You drink carefully from your flask and eat nothing and watch the sky.
  @if check bushcraft hard {
    By full dark the cloud has cleared enough. You find your fixed point, steady and certain, exactly where it should be. You take a bearing and hold it in your head as precisely as you can while you move, checking every gap in the cloud cover, building a picture of the landscape in the dark. The ground stays treacherous; once you stop yourself mid-step as your foot finds nothing. But you move with the deliberate care of someone who knows where they're going and is choosing each footfall.

    Dawn finds you at the edge of the karst, where the limestone gives way to scrub and the first proper trail in days crosses your path. You eat and keep moving.
    +remove_condition lost
    +advance_time 3
  } @else {
    The cloud comes back before you have a fix. You move anyway, a direction that feels right, which is not the same as a direction that is right. You cross the karst in the dark, where every unseen edge is a guess and the fissures are invisible until you're on them. Twice you go down hard. By dawn you've covered distance but not necessarily useful distance, and it's only when the light returns that you can place yourself and correct your bearing.

    You come out of the karst with shaking hands and several hours lost to wrong directions.
    +remove_condition lost
    +advance_time 6
    +damage_spirits 2
    +add_condition injured
  }

* Follow the clan markers = Someone placed these deliberately; they lead somewhere
  The stacked stones have a logic you can't quite articulate: certain arrangements, a consistent pattern in how the capstones are placed. You follow the line east, moving carefully over ground that sounds different in some places than it should.
  @if check cunning medium {
    You read the markers right. The arrangement repeats with only one variation, and that variation turns out to mark a fork, one direction toward a known shelter, you realize, when the route opens onto a carved threshold in the limestone, a herder's seasonal cache with a fire-blackened ceiling and a stack of dry fuel. The cache tells you where you are. From here you can plot the route back to the road.
    +remove_condition lost
    +advance_time 4
  } @else {
    The markers stop at a place where the limestone opens into a wide depression ringed with fissures. Either the route continues somewhere you can't see, or the markers served a different purpose than you assumed. You stand at the edge of the depression for a long time, listening to nothing. The wind has stopped entirely. You retreat and find your way out by other means, slower, picking across the karst by daylight until the terrain finally resolves into something you can navigate.
    +remove_condition lost
    +advance_time 6
    +damage_spirits 1
  }

* Shelter and wait for dawn = Stop moving, conserve what you have, navigate when you can see
  There is no good option in the dark over ground like this. You find the deepest part of the fissure, pull rock and dead scrub into a rough windbreak, and settle in. The cold comes up through the limestone. You don't sleep exactly; you enter a state somewhere between vigilance and exhaustion, listening to the distant sound of the karst settling, the low subsonic resonance of empty chambers far below. By first light you have a bearing. You move stiffly and slowly, but you move.
  +remove_condition lost
  +advance_time 6
  +damage_spirits 1
